Chapter 1
Cohren
0430 Itania-Time. Cohren hated waking up so early. He hated it especially because he was responsible for waking up all the others in his squad. He quietly got up from his bunk, put on his combat suit, threw his body armor over, and retrieved his belongings from the locker, being careful with a certain small box. He slung his rifle over his shoulder and attached his helmet to a small hook on his belt. Hanging from the hook was everything he needed, like his breathing apparatus or his special goggles. After checking his ammunition pouches, he quietly left the barracks. Outside, sludge and ice crunched under his boots.
He took a match from one jacket pocket and a cigarette from the other. He lit it and took a short puff before slightly opening the door. In the last week, he had to come up with a lot of tricks to wake up the men and women under his command. He no longer used the pre-set wake-up alarm, because it usually didn't work and all that came out of the speakers was a faint noise.
"Wake them up?" Cohren turned around and saw Squad Leader Nemic approaching him.
"Yes," answered Cohren.
"What are you going to try this time?"
Before he could answer, the door opened and Harris, Craith, and a few others came toward him already in full gear.
"Good morning," said Craith.
"What woke you up?" asked Cohren.
"So, first of all, we didn't want to wait to see what you'd come up with today. And secondly, the shock troops, who are the first to get up, get to choose the morning ration," answered one of the men, Ravik. "And you know how bad the food can be."
"Good point, Sergeant," said Cohren. He reached in and pressed a switch. A loud, shrill alarm sounded throughout the barracks. Inside, he heard quiet cursing and people running around in confusion."
"Come on, Valturi," said Nemic. "You'd think they'd have learned by now to wake up at the same time as you."
"Well, my people from the training camp have learned," replied Cohren, pointing at Harris, Craith, and Ravik. "However, the platoon and squad leaders also know that they have to get up before their units."
A few seconds later, the rest of the squad came out. They had everything they needed, from personal items to the necessary equipment. Some of the newer recruits looked confused, while others seemed more upset.
"Good morning," said Cohren in a good mood.
"With all due respect, sir, why do you have to wake us up like this?" asked a corporal from the shock troops.
"Because the regular alarms are crap and because Daybreak doesn't sleep," said Cohren.
"Pack all your personal belongings," Cohren continued. As the senior lieutenant and executive officer of the company, he was responsible for overseeing and supporting them together with the company commander, Major Boradin Shaw. "We are not coming back here. Sergeants and lieutenants, you and your squads have 15 minutes for the final checks and to pack your daily rations."
The members of the Exodus Company dispersed quickly. They were part of the second shock troop division, second army. Before they were merged, they were two companies, Cohort and Dagger. The company was split, and that was the main reason why Cohren had mixed feelings about his promotion to lieutenant colonel.
Cohren and Nemic, the leader of the first squad, walked side by side in the light of the many generator-powered lamps of the forward operations base. Most of them had red-tinted glass to avoid being detected by enemy bombers. Daybreak had resorted to Wild-Weasel attacks from the air and on the ground to combat them.
“A new day and a new task for the Hellhounds,” said Nemic with a dry laugh. “Where are they sending us?”
“A forward operations base outside of Ianlos. We will support the ground assault,” answered Cohren and pulled on his cigarette. He gave Craith partial credit for starting to smoke, but a year in combat changes a person, so he said nothing.
“Damn. Things are getting worse at the front,” muttered Nemic. “All the messages say: «Support the war efforts. Send help to the Kurgan Front.» How about help for the Howland Front?”
“Amen, brother,” said Cohren and flicked the remnants of his cigarette into the mud. “At least we're starting with the first armed squad and don't have to run. Captain Shaw should already be here.”
“Did Shaw arrange a ride for us?” Nemic asked a bit surprised.
“Yes. He's honestly not as bad as I thought. Not particularly friendly, but you can put up with him.”
Cohren raised his thumb and index finger to his throat microphone and adjusted his pack as he did so. “All units of the Exodus Company will meet at West Garage when they're done. We're departing with the first armed squad at 0500.”
In rapid succession, he received responses from the squad leaders. Haris, Craith, and Ravik were low-ranking non-commissioned officers when they all came here. The four had been close friends since their return to Earth. Cohren felt like he had known them forever, although it had only been at most two years. They were squad leaders, though Craith had been leading the second squad for a week, after the previous leader had been discharged for medical reasons following being shot by a Daybreak sniper.
On the way to the garage, Cohren and Nemic noticed a group of about eight Kronos combat tanks and four infantry tanks. Their crews were running around ensuring their machines were combat-ready. Quickly, Cohren spotted Major Boradin Shaw talking to the commander of the armed squad. As they approached, Shaw looked over at them and came toward them, as always with an expressionless face.
"Lieutenant Nemic… Lieutenant Valturi…" He said, Cohren was slower, while he looked at Cohren's pistol holster and then looked up again. "The company is ready, I assume?"
